ottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Salceto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Francisco, Rafael, Ana, Jesus, Carlos, Manuel, Miguel, Pedro, Jorge.","Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Salcedo, named with a collective form of <i>salce</i> ‘willow tree’, or a topographic name denoting someone living by willow trees. Compare   Saucedo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Salcido","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jesus, Carlos, Juan, Ruben, Luis, Roberto, Raul, Francisco, Juana, Adelina.","Hispanic (Mexico): probably an altered form of Spanish   Salcedo  ."]},{"name":"Saucedo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Raul, Miguel, Roberto, Alfredo, Guadalupe.","Spanish: variant of   Salcedo  . Compare   Sausedo  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":33,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":42,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Salceto was born about 1182, in Lenton, Nottinghamshire, England, her father, Robert de Salceto III, was 24 and her mother, Beatrice FitzRalph, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Adam II de Napton. She died in 1233, in England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1182–1233":"umbes 1182–1233","1182–1233":"1182–1233","1177–1202":"1177–1202","1186–1256":"1186–1256","1197–1256":"1197–1256","1201–1256":"1201–1256","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1197":"1197","1186":"1186","1160":"1160","1182":"1182","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","